  "original_lang": "si",
  "original_title": "\u0db8\u0dd0\u0dad\u0dd2\u0dc0\u0dbb\u0dab \u0db4\u0dd2\u0dbb\u0dd2\u0dc0\u0dd0\u0dba \u0d9c\u0dd0\u0db1 \u0d85\u0d9c\u0db8\u0dd0\u0dad\u0dd2\u0d9c\u0dda \u0db4\u0dca\u200d\u0dbb\u0d9a\u0dcf\u0dc1\u0dba \u0dc3\u0db8\u0dca\u0db4\u0dd6\u0dbb\u0dca\u0dab\u0dba\u0dd9\u0db1\u0dca\u0db8 \u0dc0\u0dd0\u0dbb\u0daf\u0dd2\u0dba\u0dd2",
  "text_idx": {
    "en": {
      "title": "The Prime Minister's statement about election costs is completely wrong",
      "author": "unknown",
      "body_lines": [
        "In an interview with the Daily News, Prime Minister Ranil Wickremesinghe cites two main reasons why an election cannot be held at this time: (1) the cost to the government; and (2) the adverse effect it would have on the economy.",
        "FactCheck.lk consulted the annual performance reports and administrative reports published by the Election Commission to verify the Prime Minister's statement.",
        "The Prime Minister stated that 10 billion rupees were spent for the last election, and 20 billion rupees will be spent to hold an election at this time. However, the 2022 performance report published by the Election Commission shows that the total amount spent on the general election held on August 5, 2020 is Rs 5.7 billion, which is about half of the amount mentioned by the Prime Minister.",
        "Therefore, the figures given by the Prime Minister for the cost incurred for the last election are very different compared to the actual cost. Also, due to having to follow Covid-19 safety practices, the last election is considered to be more expensive than a normal election, so the Prime Minister said that 20 billion rupees (4 times the amount spent on the last election) will be spent to hold an election at this time. The estimate made is also baseless.",
        "In considering the effect on the economy, the Prime Minister has incorrectly defined a favorable effect as an adverse effect. In future, the candidates' campaign expenditure will be Rs. He estimates that it could be 30-40 billion.* The fact is that such spending by candidates stimulates economic activity.",
        "Also, people and organizations providing services related to election campaigns will benefit from it. Government revenue will also benefit from it. The expected tax revenue under the currently announced policies would be about 10% of GDP.** Based on the Prime Minister's estimate of campaign spending, only half of that amount would be generated as additional taxable income. Government revenue Rs. will increase by about 2 billion. This will not have a negative impact on the economy but a positive one.",
        "(i) the Prime Minister's estimate of the cost of previous and forthcoming elections, while (ii) the adverse impact on the economy of holding an election while ignoring the benefits to economic activity, campaign providers and government revenue in the statement of impact on the economy; It has been announced that it will happen. Thus, considering both these matters, the Prime Minister's statement does not reflect a correct assessment of it.",
        "* The total campaign expenditure for all candidates in the 2020 general election is Rs. A study published by the Center for Monitoring Election Violence estimated that it was between 10-13 billion.",
        "* * The average of tax revenue relative to GDP during 2019-2021 (ie, under the current president) is 9.1%.",
        "* FactCheck.lk's determination is based on the most up-to-date information available to the public. If any new information comes to light regarding each of our FactCheck.lk analysis as well as this FactCheck.lk analysis, we are ready to update this review of FactCheck.lk accordingly."
      ],
